# Introduction

Exploratory structural equation modeling (ESEM) is an increasingly popular framework for estimating large and complex factor structures. It was developed to overcome the unacceptable model fit indices often encountered in real applications of confirmatory factor analysis (CFA; Marsh et al., 2020). The particular feature of ESEM is that it permits the estimation of all the loading parameters of the measurement models by means of a rotation step, avoiding the risk of model misspecification. This is an important caveat of CFA, namely the incorrect allocation of cross-loadings in the measurement model.

<!-- which can retrieve very different patterns -->
The flexibility of ESEM comes at the expense of specifying a suitable simplicity criteria to be maximized, so that a factor solution is rotated to a loading matrix that resembles as much as possible such desired simplicity. In these regards, the gradient projection algorithm (GPA; Jennrich, 2001; Jennrich, 2002) has been the predominant computational tool for rotating loading patterns during the last twenty years. The success of GPA is instantiated by its implementation in widely used and reputed statistical programs such as MPlus [@mplus], \texttt{lavaan} [@lavaan], and \texttt{psych} [@psych], the last two of which perform the rotation step through the \texttt{GPArotation} R package [@bernaards_2005]. At difference with previously used rotation procedures like ..., GPA is simple and elegant. In fact, a general purpose optimization based on GPA can be written in about 50 lines of code in the R language ^[See the \texttt{GPForth} and \texttt{GPFoblq} functions from the \texttt{GPArotation} package, which perform orthogonal and oblique rotation, respectively.]. Moreover, GPA is based on an optimization framework where traditional step-size selection techniques (e.g., backtracking line-search or trust-region) and search directions based on first and second-order derivatives can be used [@liu_2020].

Despite its appealing features, the applications of GPA are currently limited to orthogonal and oblique rotation. In other words, all the factors are either constrained to be orthogonal or allowed to correlate. This circunstance is problematic in cases where the researchers know in advance that two sets of factors may be correlated within them but orthogonal between. For example, consider multitrait-multimethod models, in which methods and traits may correlate among them but the methods are uncorrelated with the traits. This has motivated the development of a criterion that penalizes the size of the unwanted correlations [@zhang_2019]. In other cases, imposing the orthogonality in just one factor or group of factors is desirable to render a parsimonious pattern structure. For instance, consider applications of exploratory bi-factor modeling with one or multiple general factors in which all the general factors must be orthogonal to the group factors, but could be correlated among themselves [@jennrich_2012; @jimenez_2022]. If the general factors were allowed to correlate with the group factors, then the variance explained by each kind of factor could not be disentangled, with the consequence that cross-loadings across the general factors (i.e. interstitial cross-loadings) would be biased through these inter-factor correlations.

Clearly, a generalization of the oblique and orthogonal rotations that allows for a mix of oblique and orthogonal factors within the same EFA model could aid the correct estimation of such factor structures.

# An overview of the gradient projection algorithm

\textcolor{red}{Define the Riemannian metric endowed with an inner product.}

GPA builds on differential geometry to perform optimization on nonlinear manifolds. Let $\tilde{f}$ be a function with domain in $\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$ that we aim to minimize with respect to a matrix of parameters $\mathbf{X}$. Suppose that we want to constraint the solution to lie on a nonlinear manifold $\mathcal{M}$. Let define another function $f$ with domain on $\mathcal{M}$ such that 
$$
\underset{\mathbf{X} \in \mathcal{M}}{\text{argmin}} \tilde{f}(\mathbf{X}) = \text{argmin} f(\mathbf{X}).
$$ 

Our aim is to obtain an expression for the gradient of $f$, which is different to that of $\tilde{f}$ because of the nonlinearity of $\mathcal{M}$. This is easy to see by means of the popular definition of derivative. The partial derivative of $\tilde{f}$ for the $ij$ element of $\mathbf{X}$ is
$$
\lim_{t \to 0} \frac{\tilde{f}(\mathbf{X} + t\boldsymbol{\epsilon}) - \tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})}{t},
$$ 
where $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$ is a zero matrix with the $ij$ element set to 1. Clearly, this definition makes no sense for $\tilde{f}$ when we move on a nonlinear manifold because taking a plain difference does not guarantee that the result lies on $\mathcal{M}$. In other words, plain differences cannot be interpreted as distances in nonlinear spaces.

Fortunately, there is a different definition of partial derivative that applies more generally using tangent spaces. Tangent spaces are linearizations of the manifold at a given point such that any element of the tangent space is orthogonal to that point on the manifold. By endowing it with a definition of inner product, the manifold acquires a Riemannian structure, turning it into a Riemannian manifold. This definition of inner product over the tangent space is what allows us to develop a definition of gradients on the nonlinear manifold $\mathcal{M}$. The gradient of $\tilde{f}$, $\text{grad}{\tilde{f}}$, can be defined as the unique element that satisfies $\text{D}\tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})[\mathbf{Z}] = \langle \mathbf{Z}, \text{grad}\tilde{f}(\mathbf{X}) \rangle$, where $\text{D}\tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})[\mathbf{Z}]$ is the differential of $\tilde{f}$ at $\mathbf{X}$ along the direction $\mathbf{Z}$ and $<\cdot, \cdot >$ denotes the inner product.

To show that, notice that any member of $\mathbb{R}^{n \times n}$ can be decomposed in orthogonal complements. That is, the gradient of $\tilde{f}$ evaluated at $\mathbf{X}$ may be decomposed in an element belonging to the tangent space, $\mathcal{T}_\mathbf{X}\mathcal{M}$, and another element belonging to the normal space, $\mathcal{N}_{\mathbf{X}} \mathcal{M}$:
\begin{equation} \label{orth_compl}
\text{grad}\tilde{f}(\mathbf{X}) = \text{grad} \tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})_\parallel + \text{grad} \tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})_\perp,
\end{equation} where $\text{grad} \tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})_\parallel$ and $\text{grad} \tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})_\perp$ are the projections of $\text{grad}\tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})$ onto the tangent and the normal spaces, respectively.

If $\mathbf{Z} \in \mathcal{T}_\mathbf{X}\mathcal{M}$, then $\text{grad} \tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})_\perp$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf{Z}$, and it follows that $\text{D}\tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})[\mathbf{Z}] = \langle \mathbf{Z}, \text{grad}\tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})_\parallel \rangle$. Furthermore, if $\mathbf{X} \in \mathcal{M}$, then $\text{D}{f}(\mathbf{X})[\mathbf{Z}] = \langle \mathbf{Z}, \text{grad}\tilde{f}(\mathbf{X})_\parallel \rangle$ and the gradient of $f$ at $\mathbf{X} \in \mathcal{M}$ corresponds to the projection of the euclidean gradient of $\tilde{f}$ onto the tangent space of $\mathcal{M}$.

\begin{definition}
The Riemannian gradient of $f$ at $\mathbf{X} \in \mathcal{M}$, denoted by $\text{grad}{f}$, is the unique element of $\mathcal{T}_\mathbf{X}\mathcal{M}$ that satisfies $\text{D}f(\mathbf{X})[\mathbf{Z}] = \langle \mathbf{Z}, \text{grad}f(\mathbf{X}) \rangle$ for any $\mathbf{Z} \in \mathcal{T}_\mathbf{X}\mathcal{M}$.
\end{definition}

