\begin{definition}
From Definition 4.2 in Absil et al. (2009), a retraction is a smooth map $R_\mathbf{X}: \mathcal{T}_\mathbf{X}\mathcal{M} \mapsto \mathcal{M}$ that satisfies the following conditions: \\
(1) $R_\mathbf{X}(0) = \mathbf{X}$, and \\
(2) (Rigidity condition) $DR_\mathbf{X}(0)[\mathbf{Z}] = \mathbf{Z}$, with $DR_\mathbf{X}(0): \mathcal{T}_\mathbf{X}\mathcal{M} \mapsto \mathcal{T}_\mathbf{X}\mathcal{M}$ being the identity map.
\end{definition}

Both requirements can be alternatively stated as the curve $\gamma(t) = R_\mathbf{X}(t \mathbf{Z})$ satisfying $\gamma(0) = \mathbf{X}$ and $\gamma^\prime(0) = \mathbf{Z}$.

\textcolor{red}{Describe the retractions for orthogonal and oblique rotation.}

Equipped with a suitable projection and retraction, GPA is ready to find the matrix of parameters that minimize the rotation criteria with the constraint that they are either orthogonal or oblique. 

# The partially oblique manifold

In this section, we define the manifold of rotation matrices for a mixture of orthogonal and oblique factors and provide a formula for the projection onto its tangent space and a retraction. Without loss of generality, we will treat the case of a single block of oblique factors and another block of completely orthogonal factors. However, the following results are easily generalized to any number of oblique blocks of factors.

Let $\mathcal{POB}$ denote the subspace partially oblique matrices in $\mathbb{R}^{n \times n}$ defined by
$$
\mathcal{POB}(k, q) = \left\{\mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n}: \mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{X} = \begin{bmatrix}
\mathbf{Y}_{k \times k} & \mathbf{0} \\
\mathbf{0} & \mathbf{I}_{q \times q} \\
\end{bmatrix}, \ \text{ddiag}(\mathbf{Y}) = \mathbf{I}_{k \times k}
\right\},
$$
where $k$ is the number of oblique factors in the first block and $q$ is the number of completely orthogonal factors in the second. Let
\begin{equation} \label{defining_f}
h: \mathbb{R}^{n \times n} \mapsto \mathcal{DS}\mathscr{ym}(k, q) : \mathbf{X} \mapsto h(\mathbf{X}) = \mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{X} + \mathbf{P}\text{ddiag}(\mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{X})\mathbf{P} - \mathbf{P} \mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{X} \mathbf{P} - \mathbf{I}
\end{equation}
