The rank of $\text{D}h(\mathbf{X})[\mathbf{Z}]$ is $d$ for any $\mathbf{X} \in \mathcal{POB}(k, q)$, so that $\mathcal{POB}(k, q)$ can be regarded as an *embedded submanifold* of $\mathbb{R}^{n \times n}$ with dimension $n^2 - k - q(q+1)/2$ (Proposition 3.3.3; Absil et al., 2009).

## Projection onto the tangent space of the partially oblique manifold

\begin{theorem}
The Riemannian gradient of a function $f: \mathcal{POB}(k, q) \mapsto \mathbb{R}$, denoted by $grad f$, is $grad \tilde{f}(\mathbf{X}) - \mathbf{XA}$, with $\mathbf{A} = I \circ \mathbf{V}\left( \frac{\mathbf{V}^\top \mathbf{QV}}{\mathbf{1} \mathbf{d}^\top + \mathbf{d} \mathbf{1}^\top} \right) \mathbf{V}^\top$, where $I$ is an operator that sets to zero the off-diagonal elements corresponding to the oblique factors, and $\mathbf{V}$ and $\mathbf{d}$ are the eigenvectors and eigenvalues of $\mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{X}$, respectively.
\end{theorem}

