## Retraction onto the partially oblique manifold

Now, consider the case of several blocks of oblique factors. Let \textcolor{red}{redefine $k$} to denote the number of oblique blocks of factors and
$$
\mathcal{POB}(k, q) = \left\{\mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n}: \mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{X} = \begin{bmatrix}
\mathbf{Y}_1 & \mathbf{0} & \dots  & \mathbf{0} \\
\vdots & \ddots & \mathbf{0} & \vdots \\
\vdots & \mathbf{0} & \mathbf{Y}_k & \mathbf{0} \\
\mathbf{0} & \dots & \mathbf{0} & \mathbf{I}_{q \times q} \\
\end{bmatrix}, \ \text{ddiag}(\mathbf{Y}_i) = \mathbf{I}, \forall i = \{1, \dots, k \}
\right\},
$$

At the $j$ iteration of the GPA, the update formula is $\mathbf{X}^{j+1} = R_\mathbf{X}(t\text{grad} f(\mathbf{X}^j))$. That is, we need to project $\mathbf{X}^j + t\text{grad}f(\mathbf{X}^j)$ back to $\mathcal{POB}(k, q)$ to find $\mathbf{X}^{j+1}$. The best retractions for the first block of oblique factors and for the orthogonal factors are the same as in the standard oblique and orthogonal rotation approaches, respectively. That is, a suitable retraction for the first block of oblique factors involves normalizing the first $k$ columns of $\mathbf{X}$ to the unit norm, whereas to achieve orthogonal factors, the Gram-Schmidt process is applied to the last $q$ columns of $\mathbf{X}$.

If more than one oblique block of factors existed, then the Gram-Schmidt process should be applied to the columns of $\mathbf{X}$ corresponding to these oblique factors with respect the columns of $\mathbf{X}$ that corresponds to previous oblique blocks. In this process, every column of $\mathbf{X}_{\alpha_1}$ will become orthogonal to every column in $\{\mathbf{X}_{\alpha_1}, \dots, \mathbf{X}_{\alpha_{k-1}} \}$.

