# Conclusion

Until now, EFA and ESEM has been limited to the estimation of either orthogonal or oblique factors, difficulting the estimation of models involving multiple correlated general factors and multitrait-multimethod structures. Thereby, we developed a new kind of rotation, the partially oblique rotation, that allows for concomitant orthogonal and oblique factors. We demonstrated with an empirical example from personality research that forcing the orthogonality between the group factors while allowing the general factors to correlated produce a more parsimonious interpretation of the factor structure than both a completely orthogonal or oblique rotation. 

Several authors has remarked that target rotation can be understood as a semi-confirmatory method to do EFA, and this new rotation tightens further the gap between EFA and CFA with the possibility of setting constraints for some factor correlations.





